{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 16:00:14.249881", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network connectivity and reachability\n\nSummary / short conclusion\n- The network is mostly healthy: hosts in 10.1.x/10.2.x subnets can reach central services (DHCP, DNS, the 10.200.0.0 web farm and the load balancer) and OSPF routes for the 10.x networks are present on routers.\n- One clear abnormality: hosts (10.x) cannot reach the backend web subnet 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2). Ping from a host to a backend IP returns \"Destination Net Unreachable\" from the host gateway; pings from backend hosts to the 10.x hosts also fail/timeout.\n- Localization: the 20.200.0.0/24 network is not present in the global routing domain (not in the OSPF routing tables observed on server_access_router and core routers). The backend subnet therefore is isolated from the rest of the OSPF network.\n- Root cause (probable): missing route advertisement / missing routing for 20.200.0.0/24 in FRR/OSPF (or intentionally not advertised). As a result routers in the core/distribution path do not have routes to 20.200.0.0/24 and drop/ICMP-unreach traffic to that destination.\n\nWhat I tested (commands & key results)\n1) Global reachability probe (get_reachability)\n- Many host-to-server and server-to-host reachability checks were run. Most of the 10.x <-> 10.200.0.0 service tests were successful (DHCP, DNS, web0..3, load_balancer reachable). Entries for backend_web_* -> hosts were \"unknown\" (no reachability result).\n\n2) From a sample host (host_1_1_1_1) to a backend web server:\n- ping host_1_1_1_1 -> backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2)\n  - Result: \"From 10.1.1.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Net Unreachable\" (4/4 lost)\n  - Interpretation: the immediate gateway for the host returned ICMP unreachable — i.e., router receiving the packet had no route to the destination network.\n\n3) Host configuration (host_1_1_1_1):\n- IP: 10.1.1.12/24\n- Default gateway: 10.1.1.1\n\n4) Router routing table (server_access_router):\n- Shows many 10.1.x and 10.2.x OSPF-learned routes via a neighbor, and 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (server farm).\n- There is NO route for 20.200.0.0/24 in server_access_router's routing table.\n\n5) Router routing table (router_core_1):\n- Shows 10.200.0.0/24 reachable (via the server side), but NO route for 20.200.0.0/24.\n\n6) Load balancer and backend hosts:\n- load_balancer has both addresses: 10.200.0.7/24 (server-facing) and 20.200.0.1/24 (backend-facing).\n- backend_web_0 has address 20.200.0.2/24 with default via 20.200.0.1 (load_balancer).\n- host_1_1_1_1 can ping load_balancer 10.200.0.7 successfully (rtt ~3 ms), and load_balancer can ping the host successfully — connectivity between hosts and load_balancer (10.200.0.7) is working.\n- Ping from backend_web_0 towards a host (10.1.1.12) timed out on the backend node.\n\nObserved behavior & evidence (concise)\n- Host -> 10.200.0.7 (load_balancer): OK\n- Host -> 10.200.0.3..6 (web servers, dns, dhcp): OK\n- Host -> 20.200.0.2 (backend_web_0): Destination Net Unreachable from 10.1.1.1 (host gateway)\n- server_access_router routing table: no 20.200.0.0/24 entry\n- backend hosts are configured to use load_balancer as next-hop (default via 20.200.0.1), and load_balancer has routes to both 10.200.0.0 and 20.200.0.0 subnets locally, but the rest of the OSPF domain does not know 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nLocalization — where the problem manifests and which devices/segments are implicated\n- Problem segment: 20.200.0.0/24 (backend web servers) — this subnet is isolated from the OSPF-routed network.\n- Devices directly involved:\n  - backend_web_* hosts (20.200.0.2..4) — are reachable only on their local 20.200.0.0/24 and use the load_balancer as default gateway.\n  - load_balancer (20.200.0.1 & 10.200.0.7) — connects both worlds (backend network + server farm), and is reachable from hosts on the 10.200.0.0 side.\n  - server_access_router / FRR routers (core/distribution) — none show a route to 20.200.0.0/24, so they will not forward traffic toward that network.\n- Likely locus of misconfiguration: the 20.200.0.0/24 network is not being advertised into OSPF (or appropriate static route/proxy is missing), so core/distribution routers do not have a route for that segment.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Missing route advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24 into the routed domain (OSPF). Either:\n  - The backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is intentionally not advertised (isolation by design), or\n  - The expected advertisement/origin (e.g., load_balancer or server_access_router) is not configured to inject 20.200.0.0/24 into OSPF (or FRR is not configured to redistribute it).\n- As a result, routers (including the host default gateway) return ICMP Destination Unreachable for packets destined to 20.200.0.0/24, and traffic from the 10.x networks cannot reach backend hosts. Similarly, return path to the backends from the core is missing, so backend->host pings fail/time out.\n\nImpact / scope\n- Hosts cannot reach backend web servers directly (20.200.0.0/24). This breaks any scenario that expects direct host → backend_tcp/icmp connectivity.\n- Hosts can reach the published services (10.200.0.0 web servers and the load balancer) — the user-visible services on the 10.200.0.0 network are reachable.\n- If the design intent is to keep backends unreachable from hosts (only reachable via the load balancer), the observed state is consistent with that design. If instead the design intent (per your earlier note) was to have \"all infrastructure and server networks … advertised by FRR OSPF so that hosts can resolve and access the web services end-to-end\", then the current state is a misconfiguration (20.200.0.0/24 is not advertised).\n\nAdditional notes / anomalies observed\n- The ICMP “Destination Net Unreachable” came from the host gateway (10.1.1.1) indicating the gateway/router has no route to 20.200.0.0.\n- load_balancer routing and interfaces look consistent: it has both 10.200.0.7 and 20.200.0.1 addresses and routes between those local subnets. It can talk to hosts on the 10.200.0 side (confirmed by successful pings).\n- backend_web_0 default route points to the load_balancer (20.200.0.1) — backend traffic would need the LB to forward packets into the routed domain. Because the routed domain lacks 20.200.0.0/24, the return path fails.\n- get_reachability shows backend->host checks as \"unknown\" — consistent with the missing routing.\n\nOverall assessment\n- Network control plane (OSPF/FRR) appears to be converged for the 10.x and 10.200.0.0 networks; host-to-service connectivity for the published server farm (10.200.0.0) is functioning.\n- The backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24 is isolated from the OSPF domain (not advertised/known), causing end-to-end reachability between hosts and backend_web_* to fail.\n- This is a routing/advertisement / network-segmentation issue rather than a host access or physical connectivity issue (hosts can reach load-balancer and other server farm addresses).\n\nIf you want further verification steps I can run (e.g., check FRR OSPF configuration on server_access_router or on the load_balancer, inspect whether load_balancer is running a routing protocol or NAT, show more routing tables on other routers), or collect exact OSPF configuration snippets that show which networks are being advertised. (You did not request remediation — I have not included any fixes.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 37573, "output_tokens": 5003, "total_tokens": 42576, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 37248}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3008}}}
